DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       nnggrraamm--mmeerrggee  reads  two  or  more lexicographically sorted
       ngram count files (as produced by nnggrraamm--ccoouunntt  --ssoorrtt)  and
       outputs  the  merged,  sorted  counts.  The output is thus
       suitable for subsequeunt merging steps.

       The input format consists of one ngram count per line,
            _w_o_r_d_1 _w_o_r_d_2 _._._. _w_o_r_d_n _c_o_u_n_t

       The lines must be sorted lexicographically on  the  words,
       leftmost first.  The input may contain ngrams of different
       lengths.

       Each filename argument can be a plain ascii count file, or
       a  compressed file (name ending in .Z or .gz), or ``-'' to
       indicate stdin/stdout.

       nnggrraamm--mmeerrggee is recommended in cases where the full  counts
       would far exceed available real memory.  Although an arbi-
       trary number of input count files is accepted, it is  best
       to  use  program  as  follows.  First, partition the input
       text into the largest chunks so that nnggrraamm--ccoouunntt  can  run
       in  real  memory.   Then merge the resulting sorted counts
       using nnggrraamm--mmeerrggee pairwise, and continue  doing  so  in  a
       binary  tree  pattern until a single count file containing
       all ngrams remains.

